        <Parent_String>Caucasian rugs by pattern [300233479], rugs by pattern [300187593], rugs (textiles) [300185749], coverings and hangings by form [300185748], coverings and hangings by specific type [300185832], coverings and hangings [300205012], furnishings by form or function [300037342], furnishings (works) [300037336], Furnishings (hierarchy name) [300037335], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Late-17th- and 18-century rugs, thought to have originated in the Caucasus, frequently characterized by a depressed two-level natural wool warp, wool wefts often dyed red, and knotted with symmetrical knots; the field pattern consists of a drop repeat directional lattice pattern made up of jagged leaf forms enclosing stylized dragons.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Alfombras de fines de siglo XVII y XVIII, que se cree que son originarias del Cáucaso, frecuentemente se caracterizan por una depresión natural de dos niveles en la urdimbre de la lana, las tramas de lana a menudo teñidas de rojo y anudadas con nudos simétricos; el campo de diseño consiste en repetir un modelo de celosía direccional de gotas hechas en formas de hojas puntiagudas que encierran dragones estilizados.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tapijten uit de laat-17e en 18e eeuw die waarschijnlijk oorspronkelijk uit de Kaukasus komen. Ze worden gekenmerkt door een ingedrukte wollen schering in twee niveaus en een eveneens wollen, meestal rode, symmetrische geknoopte inslag. Het veldpatroon bestaat uit een dalend herhaald rastermotief in één bepaalde richting en gekartelde bladvormen die gestileerde draken omsluiten.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052478/Kinebanian, Perzische en Oosterse tapijten</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>據信於十七世紀晚期至十八世紀間，發展於高加索一帶的毯子，特色是將兩層天然羊毛經紗壓平，羊毛緯紗經常染成紅色，飾有對稱的結。毯面為下降重複（drop repeat）的方向性格子花紋，由鋸齒葉圖形包圍著風格獨特的龍紋所組成。
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Teppich aus dem späten 17. und 18. Jahrhundert, es wird angenommen, dass er aus dem Kaukasus stammt, oft gekennzeichnet durch einen niedergedrückten zweistufigen natürlichen Woll-Kettfaden. Der Wollschuss-faden ist oft rot gefärbt und mit symmetrischen Knoten verknüpft. Das Feldmuster besteht aus einem sich wiederholenden gerichteten Gittermuster hergestellt aus gezackten Blattformen, die stilisierte Drachen umschließen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
